      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As your editorial of June 23 points out, there are things that can be done to mitigate the severity of the greenhouse effect disaster. One that you omitted is recycling, an important component of any program to combat global warming. It also has many side benefits. By reducing the energy necessary to extract, process and transport raw materials, recycling reduces the carbon dioxide emissions from fossil-fuel energy sources.</p>
        <p>Your mention of ''cheaper, safer nuclear power'' as another means of slowing global climate change is shortsighted. A wiser recommendation would be to develop cheaper photovoltaic power, which is inherently safe, environmentally benign and has a source both free and virtually endless. RICHARD GOLDEN  Dir., Climate Protection Institute  Oakland, Calif., June 23, 1988</p>
      </block>
